    {
        "content": "<p>currently all structs of a crate have to be declared inside of <code>adt_reflect</code> in order for <code>field_of!</code> to work correctly</p>",
        "id": 601493194,
        "sender_full_name": "Benno Lossin",
        "timestamp": 1781025287
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>there is a <code>field_of!</code> macro being generated by <code>adt_reflect</code></p>",
        "id": 601493333,
        "sender_full_name": "Benno Lossin",
        "timestamp": 1781025311
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I replaced <code>Pin</code> with <code>Shield</code> and a manual <code>Overwrite</code> auto-trait, we could emulate it using derives, which one would need for every struct that contains an <code>Rcu</code> (transitively, stopping at pointer boundaries). Here's a blog post from Niko on the overwrite trait: <a href=\"https://smallcultfollowing.com/babysteps/blog/2024/10/14/overwrite-and-pin/\">https://smallcultfollowing.com/babysteps/blog/2024/10/14/overwrite-and-pin/</a></p>",
        "id": 601542494,
        "sender_full_name": "Benno Lossin",
        "timestamp": 1781035703
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>it could fit well into the <code>Move</code>, <code>Forget</code> and <code>Leak</code> hierarchy that we already want to have</p>",
        "id": 601542675,
        "sender_full_name": "Benno Lossin",
        "timestamp": 1781035743
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>if we had that trait in std and proper support for <code>Overwrite</code>, then we could just use normal DerefMut in the write path</p>",
        "id": 601542909,
        "sender_full_name": "Benno Lossin",
        "timestamp": 1781035789
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I like the name <code>Shield</code> ;-)</p>",
